I now have full grounding. The existing commonMain has only `Greeting.kt`/`Platform.kt` scaffolding, and the package root is `com.radiacode.shared`. I have everything needed to produce a concrete design.

Here is the complete Branch-1 design.

---

# RadiaCode KMP Protocol Codec — Branch-1 Design

## 0. Design principles (grounded in the verified Swift source)

The Swift transport (`Peripheral.swift` / `DeviceTransmition.swift`) uses exactly four touch-points against the command layer, and these define the Kotlin public API contract:

1. `command.storageType.instance` → a fresh mutable `BluetoothRawStorage`
2. `command.requestPackage()` → `[Data]` (the BLE write packets)
3. `storage.append(bytes:)` per notification, then check `storage.isLastPackage`
4. `command.response.decode(storage)` → typed `T.Response`

Branch-1 reproduces these four seams in pure Kotlin with byte-for-byte parity, no hardware, no coroutines, no transport. The Swift app will *not* be rewired in this branch — it keeps its own Swift codec. Branch-1 only lands the Kotlin port + tests so parity is provable before any consumer migrates.

---

## 1. Package layout

Root package is `com.radiacode.shared` (matches existing `Greeting.kt`). Add a `ble` subtree:

```
shared/src/commonMain/kotlin/com/radiacode/shared/
├── ble/
│   ├── protocol/
│   │   ├── BluetoothCommandType.kt          // type register codes (4 entries)
│   │   ├── BluetoothCommandOperation.kt     // ~53 op codes
│   │   ├── BluetoothCommandRequest.kt       // request model (data class)
│   │   ├── RequestSerializer.kt             // commandData + framing -> List<ByteArray>
│   │   ├── BluetoothRawStorage.kt           // interface + isLastPackage default
│   │   ├── DefaultBluetoothRawStorage.kt    // validation-key framing
│   │   ├── SystemBluetoothRawStorage.kt     // no-validation framing
│   │   ├── StorageType.kt                   // Default | System | Custom
│   │   └── BluetoothCommandParseError.kt    // exception type
│   ├── command/
│   │   ├── BluetoothCommand.kt              // the command abstraction (see §2.4)
│   │   └── system/
